## Files — plain text, portable, future-proof

iA Writer saves everything as **plain-text files with Markdown formatting**. No proprietary database or format. Every file opens in any text editor (Notepad, VS Code, Obsidian). This is a core philosophical commitment — the writing belongs to the writer, not the app.

### Change the default extension immediately

iA Writer defaults to saving files with a **`.txt` extension**, not `.md`. First configuration step after installation: **Settings → Files → Default Extension → `.md`**. This ensures files are recognized correctly by GitHub, AI context tools, and any other Markdown-aware software.

Files use **UTF-8 encoding** with full Unicode support.

### Cloud sync on Windows

iA Writer has no sync engine of its own — it reads and writes to local folders, and the cloud provider's desktop client handles sync. Folders are added as **Locations** in iA Writer's Library.

| Cloud Service | Windows Support | Notes |
|---------------|----------------|-------|
| **Dropbox** | ✅ | Most reliable on Windows — recommended |
| **OneDrive** | ✅ | Built into Windows 11, solid |
| **Google Drive** | ✅ | Install desktop client, add folder as Location |
| **iCloud** | ✅ | Requires iCloud for Windows app — update to latest version first. Known occasional sync failures — iA acknowledges it "works nicely, but there are annoying cases where it just fails" |
| Any local folder | ✅ | Any File Explorer-accessible folder |

**Best practice:** Use Dropbox or OneDrive for the most reliable Windows sync. Verify files have synced (check timestamps in File Explorer) before editing on another device. Never edit the same file on two devices simultaneously — version conflicts require manual resolution.

